            <person xml:id="pers1235">
               <p>Born in <placeName>Londonderry Ireland</placeName>, in a home where <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and his preachers were often
                  entertained, Knox broke with Methodism by the age of 20 and joined the Church of
                     <placeName>England</placeName>. Despite poor health, he became for a while
                  private secretary to <persName>Lord Castlereagh</persName>. Then he retired from
                  public life to a quest for spiritual holiness, during which he carried on frequent
                  correspondence with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>.
                  See <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 195;
                  and <hi rend="italic">WHS</hi> 22 (<date when="1939">1939</date>): 67– 71.</p>
